        "answer": "The separation rule says that shaded cells cannot touch each other horizontally or vertically.\n\nLet's say we try shading r3c8. Since r2c8 and r3c8 are next to each other, if we shade r3c8, then r2c8 must be unshaded to follow the separation rule.\n\nBut this creates a problem because in the same column (column 8), both r2c8 and r3c8 have the same symbol. According to the uniqueness rule, only one of them can remain unshaded. Since we've shaded r3c8, r2c8 must be unshaded.\n\nHowever, this leads to a contradiction because if r2c8 is unshaded and r3c8 is shaded, they still share an edge, which violates the separation rule. Therefore, our initial assumption that r3c8 can be shaded is incorrect.\n\nAs a result, r3c8 must remain unshaded to avoid breaking the separation rule.",
